{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem *Zuhd aur Rindi* (\"Asceticism and Libertinism\") from *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, the ascetic (*zahid*, representative of *zuhd*) and the wine-drinker (*rind*, representative of *rindi*) are directly juxtaposed in the opening narrative, where the poet describes his long acquaintance with a cleric (the zahid figure) who critiques him (Iqbal as rind). The key lines are:\n\n> For many years he was a neighbor mine,  \n> So Saint and Sinner would their paths align.[^1]\n\nThis captures their intertwined lives and contrasts (*zahid ki mulaqat... rind se* in the original Urdu). The theme permeates the poem, as the cleric later puzzles over Iqbal's blend of sinner/libertine (*rindi*) knowledge and strict law (*shariat*, aligned with asceticism): \n\n> “He knows the Sinner’s path, the Law’s decree,  \n> In mystic lore, a new Mansur is he.[^2]\n\nThe cleric himself embodies a hypocritical fusion, with his \"heart’s own flask with pious wine... / But dregs of pride were secretly distilled,\"[^3] equating ascetic \"pious wine\" (*mai-e-zuhd*) to the rind's metaphorical wine.\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Zuhd aur Rindi\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/44-zuhd-aur-rindi/translation/#p-34574a).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Zuhd aur Rindi\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/44-zuhd-aur-rindi/translation/#p-ea39dc).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, \"Zuhd aur Rindi\" [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/44-zuhd-aur-rindi/translation/#p-52b34d#p-f39e58).",
